<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-585-031  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 585 031.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Nov 5 1990 v7 n45 p45(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multivendor platforms will allow for true integration.andO;(vendor-independent network and system management platforms)(Opinions)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Herman, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Vendors including DEC, HP and Sun Microsystems Inc designgeneral-purpose management systems that provide the foundation forbuilding device-specific management products.andP;  In response toinadequate management system functionality, these platforms offerthe basic services that users require in their managementapplications including myriad management protocols, a managementuser interface and management data storage.andP;  In addition to usingobject-oriented programming and data definition techniques, theyfeature the latest distributed system concepts of client/servercomputing such as remote procedure call.andP;  Eventually, users willbe able to purchase highly functional management applicationmodules from different vendors that can run on the same platform.andO;Vendors will need to establish a standard platform on which tobuild their applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ManagementAttitudeMarket EntryMultivendor SystemsInteroperabilityStandardsIntegrated SoftwareTrendsManagement Applications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>